description: From Middle English dull, dul (also dyll, dill, dwal), from Old English dol (“dull, foolish, erring, heretical; foolish, silly; presumptuous”), from Proto-West Germanic *dol, from Proto-Germanic *dulaz, from earlier *dwulaz, a variant of *dwalaz (“stunned, mad, foolish, misled”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰwel-, *dʰewel- (“to dim, dull, cloud, make obscure, swirl, whirl”).

Cognate with Scots dull, doll (“slow to understand or hear, deaf, dull”), North Frisian dol (“rash, unthinking, giddy, flippant”), Dutch dol (“crazy, mad, insane”), Low German dul, dol (“mad, silly, stupid, fatuous”), German toll (“crazy, mad, wild, fantastic”), Danish dval (“foolish, absurd”), Icelandic dulur (“secretive, silent”), West-Flemish dul (angry, furious).

entries.meaning: Lacking the ability to cut easily; not sharp.

examples: He sat through the dull lecture and barely stayed awake.

entries.meaning: Not shiny; having a matte finish or no particular luster or brightness.
examples: Choose a dull finish to hide fingerprints.
a dull fire or lamp;  a dull red or yellow;  a dull mirror

entries.meaning: Not bright or intelligent; stupid; having slow understanding.

examples: As turning the logs will make a dull fire burn, so changes of study a dull brain.

entries.meaning: (of pain etc) Not intense; felt indistinctly or only slightly.
examples: Pressing on the bruise produces a dull pain.

entries.meaning: (of a noise or sound) Not clear, muffled.

verbs.description: dull (third-person singular simple present dulls, present participle dulling, simple past and past participle dulled)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To render dull; to remove or blunt an edge or something that was sharp.
examples: Years of misuse have dulled the tools.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To soften, moderate or blunt; to make dull, stupid, or sluggish; to stupefy.
examples: He drinks to dull the pain.

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To lose a sharp edge; to become dull.
examples: A razor will dull with use.

entries.meaning: To render dim or obscure; to sully; to tarnish.
